<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Marking Scheme - Grade 9 Math Final Exam</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
            line-height: 1.6;
            color: #333;
            max-width: 1000px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1, h2, h3 {
            color: #1a4b84;
        }
        .header {
            text-align: center;
            border-bottom: 2px solid #1a4b84;
            padding-bottom: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .curriculum-notes {
            background-color: #f8f9fa;
            border-left: 5px solid #1a4b84;
            padding: 15px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            font-size: 0.95em;
        }
        table {
            width: 100%;
            border-collapse: collapse;
            margin-bottom: 30px;
        }
        th, td {
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            padding: 12px;
            text-align: left;
            vertical-align: top;
        }
        th {
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
            color: #333;
        }
        .points {
            font-weight: bold;
            color: #d9534f;
            white-space: nowrap;
            text-align: center;
        }
        .fraction {
            display: inline-block;
            text-align: center;
            vertical-align: middle;
            margin: 0 0.2em;
        }
        .fraction > span {
            display: block;
            padding: 0.1em;
        }
        .fraction span.fdn {
            border-top: 1px solid #000;
        }
        code {
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            padding: 2px 4px;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div class="header">
        <h1>Beit Jala School</h1>
        <h2>Grade 9 (Brevet) - Mathematics Final Exam Marking Scheme</h2>
        <p><strong>June 2026 | Total Grades: 20 | Time: 2 hours</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="curriculum-notes">
        <h3>Lebanese Brevet Curriculum Evaluation Notes</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Methodology over Final Answer:</strong> Partial grades must be awarded for recognizing correct theorems (e.g., Thales, Pythagoras) even if calculation errors occur later.</li>
            <li><strong>Exact Values:</strong> Unless decimal rounding is explicitly requested, results must be kept as simplified fractions or simplified radicals (e.g., 4&radic;2, not 5.65).</li>
            <li><strong>Geometric Justification:</strong> Properties such as "tangent is perpendicular to radius" or "altitudes intersecting at orthocenter" must be explicitly written out by the student to earn full points.</li>
            <li><strong>Domains of Definition:</strong> For algebraic fractions, rejecting a root because it falls out of the domain of definition is a crucial competency. Failure to justify the rejection results in deduction.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Part I: Multiple Choice Questions (4 pts)</h2>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th width="10%">Q No.</th>
            <th width="70%">Correct Answer & Justification</th>
            <th width="20%">Points</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Answer depends on exam graphic. (Usually 4/5 or 3/5)</strong><br>
                <em>Justification:</em> In a right triangle, cos(C) = Adjacent / Hypotenuse. (Ensure student selected the option matching the specific lengths in the provided figure).
            </td>
            <td class="points">1 pt</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2</td>
            <td>
                <strong>(a) 80 $</strong><br>
                <em>Justification:</em> Let x be the original price. x + 0.20x = 96 &rArr; 1.2x = 96 &rArr; x = 96 / 1.2 = 80.
            </td>
            <td class="points">1 pt</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>3</td>
            <td>
                <strong>(a) &radic;2 + 1</strong><br>
                <em>Justification:</em> Multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate (&radic;2 + 1). <br>
                1 / (&radic;2 - 1) = (&radic;2 + 1) / (2 - 1) = &radic;2 + 1.
            </td>
            <td class="points">1 pt</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>4</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Evaluate based on specific table given in exam.</strong><br>
                <em>Note to grader:</em> The prompt text was partially truncated. Grade based on correct cross-multiplication or proportional simplification.
            </td>
            <td class="points">1 pt</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Part II: Algebraic Expressions (4 pts)</h2>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th width="10%">Part</th>
            <th width="70%">Detailed Working</th>
            <th width="20%">Points</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>a)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Factorize B(x):</strong><br>
                B(x) = 9x<sup>2</sup> - 4 = (3x)<sup>2</sup> - 2<sup>2</sup> = <strong>(3x - 2)(3x + 2)</strong>
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>b)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Verify A(x):</strong><br>
                A(x) = (3x - 2)<sup>2</sup> - (2x - 1)(3x - 2)<br>
                A(x) = (3x - 2) [ (3x - 2) - (2x - 1) ]<br>
                A(x) = (3x - 2) (3x - 2 - 2x + 1)<br>
                <strong>A(x) = (3x - 2)(x - 1)</strong>
            </td>
            <td class="points">1.00 pt</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>c)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Solve B(x) = 9:</strong><br>
                9x<sup>2</sup> - 4 = 9 &rArr; 9x<sup>2</sup> = 13 &rArr; x<sup>2</sup> = 13/9<br>
                <strong>x = &radic;13 / 3</strong> OR <strong>x = -&radic;13 / 3</strong>
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>d) i.</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Domain of F(x):</strong><br>
                Denominator &ne; 0 &rArr; (3x - 2)(x - 1) &ne; 0.<br>
                <strong>x &ne; 2/3</strong> and <strong>x &ne; 1</strong>
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>d) ii.</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Simplify F(x):</strong><br>
                F(x) = [ (3x - 2)(3x + 2) ] / [ (3x - 2)(x - 1) ] = <strong>(3x + 2) / (x - 1)</strong>
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>d) iii.</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Solve F(x) = -12:</strong><br>
                (3x + 2) / (x - 1) = -12 &rArr; 3x + 2 = -12(x - 1) &rArr; 3x + 2 = -12x + 12<br>
                15x = 10 &rArr; x = 10/15 = 2/3.<br>
                <em>Justification:</em> <strong>No solution.</strong> x = 2/3 is rejected because it is excluded from the domain of definition.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Part III: Probabilities and Statistics (2.5 pts)</h2>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th width="10%">Part</th>
            <th width="70%">Detailed Working</th>
            <th width="20%">Points</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Percentages:</strong><br>
                Green balls = (2/5) &times; 100% = <strong>40%</strong>.<br>
                Black balls = 100% - (10% + 15% + 40%) = 100% - 65% = <strong>35%</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">1.00 pt<br>(0.5 ea)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Total Number of Balls:</strong><br>
                Let T be the total number of balls. 35% of T = 42.<br>
                0.35 &times; T = 42 &rArr; T = 42 / 0.35 = <strong>120 balls</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">1.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Part IV: Coordinate Geometry (5.5 pts)</h2>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th width="10%">Part</th>
            <th width="70%">Detailed Working</th>
            <th width="20%">Points</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1)</td>
            <td><strong>Plotting:</strong> Correct placement of A(4, 2), B(-2, -2), and C(-1, 3) on the orthonormal system.</td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Verify points on (d): y = 5x + 8</strong><br>
                For B: 5(-2) + 8 = -10 + 8 = -2 = y<sub>B</sub>. (B belongs to d)<br>
                For C: 5(-1) + 8 = -5 + 8 = 3 = y<sub>C</sub>. (C belongs to d)<br>
                <em>Drawing:</em> Straight line drawn correctly passing through B and C.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>3)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Equation of (AC):</strong><br>
                Slope a = (y<sub>C</sub> - y<sub>A</sub>) / (x<sub>C</sub> - x<sub>A</sub>) = (3 - 2) / (-1 - 4) = -1/5.<br>
                y - y<sub>A</sub> = a(x - x<sub>A</sub>) &rArr; y - 2 = -1/5(x - 4) &rArr; <strong>y = -1/5x + 14/5</strong>
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>4) a)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Lengths:</strong><br>
                AC = &radic;[(-1 - 4)<sup>2</sup> + (3 - 2)<sup>2</sup>] = &radic;[25 + 1] = <strong>&radic;26</strong><br>
                BC = &radic;[(-1 - -2)<sup>2</sup> + (3 - -2)<sup>2</sup>] = &radic;[1 + 25] = <strong>&radic;26</strong>
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>4) b)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Show Perpendicularity:</strong><br>
                Slope of (AC) = -1/5. Slope of (BC) [line d] = 5.<br>
                m<sub>AC</sub> &times; m<sub>BC</sub> = (-1/5) &times; 5 = -1. Therefore, <strong>(AC) &perp; (BC)</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>4) c)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Nature of ABC:</strong><br>
                Since AC = BC and angle C = 90&deg;, ABC is a <strong>right isosceles triangle at C</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.25 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>5) a)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Circle Circumscribed:</strong><br>
                Since ABC is right at C, hypotenuse [AB] is the diameter. Center I is the midpoint of [AB].<br>
                x<sub>I</sub> = (4 - 2)/2 = 1. y<sub>I</sub> = (2 - 2)/2 = 0. <strong>I(1, 0)</strong>.<br>
                Radius = AB / 2 = &radic;[(-2-4)<sup>2</sup> + (-2-2)<sup>2</sup>] / 2 = &radic;52 / 2 = 2&radic;13 / 2 = <strong>&radic;13</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>5) b)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Belongs to x-axis:</strong><br>
                Since the ordinate (y-coordinate) of I is 0, it lies on the x-axis.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.25 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>6) a)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Nature of CBDA:</strong><br>
                I is midpoint of [AB] and [CD] (by symmetry). Diagonals bisect each other &rArr; parallelogram.<br>
                Parallelogram with a right angle (angle C = 90&deg;) &rArr; rectangle.<br>
                Rectangle with adjacent equal sides (AC = BC) &rArr; <strong>Square</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>6) b)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Coordinates of D:</strong><br>
                x<sub>I</sub> = (x<sub>C</sub> + x<sub>D</sub>)/2 &rArr; 1 = (-1 + x<sub>D</sub>)/2 &rArr; x<sub>D</sub> = 3.<br>
                y<sub>I</sub> = (y<sub>C</sub> + y<sub>D</sub>)/2 &rArr; 0 = (3 + y<sub>D</sub>)/2 &rArr; y<sub>D</sub> = -3.<br>
                <strong>D(3, -3)</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Part V: Pure Geometry (4 pts)</h2>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th width="10%">Part</th>
            <th width="70%">Detailed Working</th>
            <th width="20%">Points</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1)</td>
            <td><strong>Reproduce the figure:</strong> Accuracy of the drawn circle, tangents, and point projections.</td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Nature of ODE and DE length:</strong><br>
                (ED) is tangent to (C) at D &rArr; (OD) &perp; (ED). Triangle ODE is <strong>right at D</strong>.<br>
                E is symmetric to A wrt B &rArr; AB = BE = 4 cm. OE = OB + BE = 2 + 4 = 6 cm. OD = radius = 2 cm.<br>
                By Pythagoras in ODE: DE<sup>2</sup> + OD<sup>2</sup> = OE<sup>2</sup> &rArr; DE<sup>2</sup> + 4 = 36 &rArr; DE = &radic;32 = <strong>4&radic;2 cm</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>3)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Parallel lines:</strong><br>
                (OD) &perp; (ED) [Tangent property].<br>
                (FB) &perp; (ED) [Given, F is orthogonal projection].<br>
                Two lines perpendicular to the same line are parallel. <strong>(DO) // (FB)</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>4)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Calculate BF and EF using Thales:</strong><br>
                In &Delta;ODE, since (FB) // (OD), apply Thales's Theorem:<br>
                EF / ED = EB / EO = FB / OD.<br>
                EB / EO = 4 / 6 = 2/3.<br>
                EF = DE &times; (2/3) = 4&radic;2 &times; (2/3) = <strong>(8&radic;2) / 3 cm</strong>.<br>
                FB = OD &times; (2/3) = 2 &times; (2/3) = <strong>4/3 cm</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">1.00 pt</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>5)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Calculate tan(E):</strong><br>
                In right triangle DEO, tan(E) = Opposite / Adjacent = OD / DE = 2 / 4&radic;2 = 1 / 2&radic;2 = <strong>&radic;2 / 4</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.50 pts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>6)</td>
            <td>
                <strong>Show (KO) &perp; (ME):</strong><br>
                In triangle MOE:<br>
                1. (d) is tangent at A &rArr; (MA) &perp; (OE). Thus, (MA) is the altitude from M.<br>
                2. (ED) is tangent at D &rArr; (ED) &perp; (MO). Thus, (ED) is the altitude from E.<br>
                The intersection of these two altitudes, point K, is the <strong>orthocenter</strong> of &Delta;MOE.<br>
                The line passing through the orthocenter K and the third vertex O is the third altitude. Therefore, <strong>(KO) &perp; (ME)</strong>.
            </td>
            <td class="points">0.75 pts</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

